uestions about its relationship to neoliberalism, the policing of sexual cultures, and the broader context of social justice organizing at the turn of the twenty-first century. Montegary’s investigation of the politics of LGBT family life takes us on a journey that includes not only activist events and the courtrooms where landmark decisions about same-sex families were made, but also parenting workshops, cruise ships, and gay resort towns. Through its sustained historical analysis, Familiar Perversions lays critical groundwork for imagining a queer family movement that can support and strengthen the diverse networks of care, kinship, and intimacy on which our collective survival depends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomics. 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aFamilieszUnited States. 0aFamilies. 0aFamily policyzUnited States. 0aGay parentszUnited States. 0aGay rightszUnited States. 0aPolitical science. 0aPolitics, Practical. 0aRace. 0aSex. 0aSexual minorities' familieszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aLGBT.  aeconomic.  afamily equality movement.  afamily.  apolitics.  arace.  asame-sex.  asex.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081359139140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813591391423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813591391.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK